lkshire, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Verdon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Marcel, Pierre, Renaud, Sylvie.","French: habitational name from (Le) Verdon, the name of several places in various parts of France, for example in Dordogne, Gironde, and Marne. Compare   Ferdon  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Verdun, the name of a fief in Vessey (Manche), France. Compare   Verdun  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Verdin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Ramon, Angel, Luis, Ruben, Azael, Fernando, Fidel, Francisco, Guillermo, Javier.","English (Lancashire and Cheshire): variant of   Verdon  .","Altered form of French   Verdun  ."]},{"name":"Ferdon","meanings":["Altered form, under American Dutch influence in New Netherland, of French   Verdon  ."]},{"name":"Wearden","meanings":["English (Lancashire): apparently from a placename with Old English <i>denu</i> ‘valley’ as the second element. However, the Victoria County History for Staffordshire identifies John <i>de Werdon</i>, mentioned in 1280, as having his name from Verdun (Manche, France); see   Verdon  ."]},{"name":"Verdun","meanings":["French: habitational name from any of several places in France called Verdun. The placename is probably of Gaulish origin, deriving from <i>ver(n)</i> ‘alder’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill, fortress’.","Spanish and Catalan: habitational name from Verdú in Catalonia (Spain), which has the same origin as the French name (see 1 above).","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Verdon  , a cognate of 1 above. This surname is very rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":40,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":49,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William De Verdon was born in 1175, in Bressingham, Norfolk, England as the son of William de Verdun and Mrs William de Verdun. He married Mrs Maud De William about 1191, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1242, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1175–1242":"1175–1242","1174–1244":"1174–1244","1192–1229":"1192–1229","1212–Female":"1212–Surnud","1218–1277":"1218–1277","1155–1197":"1155–1197","–Female":"Surnud","about 1191":"umbes 1191","AFT 1229":"pärast 1229","1242":"1242","1175":"1175","1197":"1197","1174":"1174","1192":"1192","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1212":"1212","1277":"1277","1244":"1244","1155":"1155","before 1175":"enne 1175","Aft 1197":"pärast 1197","ABT 1192":"umbes 1192","1218":"1218","1229":"1229","Aslacton, Norfolk, England":"Aslacton, Norfolk, England","Depwade Dist, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of,Framlingham,Suffolk,England":"Framlingham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Bressingham, Norfolk, England":"Bressingham, Norfolk, England",", Suffolkshire, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1175–1242":"1175–1242","1174–1244":"1174–1244","1192–1229":"1192–1229","1212–Female":"1212–Kuollut","1218–1277":"1218–1277","1155–1197":"1155–1197","–Female":"Kuollut","about 1191":"noin 1191","AFT 1229":"1229 jälkeen","1242":"1242","1175":"1175","1197":"1197","1174":"1174","1192":"1192","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1212":"1212","1277":"1277","1244":"1244","1155":"1155","before 1175":"ennen vuotta 1175","Aft 1197":"1197 jälkeen","ABT 1192":"noin 1192","1218":"1218","1229":"1229","Aslacton, Norfolk, England":"Aslacton, Norfolk, England","Depwade Dist, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Of,Framlingham,Suffolk,England":"Framlingham, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Bressingham, Norfolk, Engla